---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
const draft = true; // STAGED: remove this line on publish date
const faqSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Do I have to disclose termite history when selling my Brisbane property?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes. In Queensland, sellers must disclose known defects that would not be apparent to a buyer on reasonable inspection. Known termite damage or active termite activity is a latent defect and must be disclosed in the contract. Concealing it creates significant legal liability."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Should I get termite treatment done before listing my Brisbane property?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "If there is active termite activity, yes. Treat first, obtain a clearance report from a licensed pest controller, and have that documentation ready for buyers. A property with a current termite management system and clean clearance report sells more confidently than one where treatment happened but no documentation exists."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What do buyers and their inspectors look for in a building and pest report regarding termites?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "B&P inspectors check for live termite activity, termite workings, past damage to structural and non-structural timber, the condition of any existing chemical barrier or bait station system, drainage and moisture conditions that attract termites, and evidence of previous repairs to termite-affected timber. They report on both active and historical evidence."
      }
    }
  ]
};
---
<Layout title="Termite Management and Selling a Brisbane Property: What Sellers Must Know | Daniel Gierach Property" description="Termites are a significant consideration for Brisbane property sellers. Here is what you need to know about disclosure, treatment, documentation, and managing buyer confidence." draft={draft}>

<script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(faqSchema)}></script>

<article style="background:var(--color-surface-0);min-height:100vh;">

  <!-- Hero -->
  <div style="background:#0a0806;padding:8rem 0 3rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8">
      <a href="/insights" style="display:inline-flex;align-items:center;gap:0.5rem;font-family:var(--font-sans);font-size:0.65rem;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:0.14em;text-transform:uppercase;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.35);text-decoration:none;margin-bottom:2rem;transition:color 0.2s;"
        onmouseover="this.style.color='#f5d07a'" onmouseout="this.style.color='rgba(240,236,228,0.35)'">
        &larr; All Articles
      </a>
      <span style="display:block;font-family:var(--font-sans);font-size:0.6rem;font-weight:800;letter-spacing:0.2em;text-transform:uppercase;color:#f5d07a;margin-bottom:1rem;">Sellers &middot; 6 min read</span>
      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        Termite Management and Selling a Brisbane Property: What Sellers Must Know
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Brisbane's subtropical climate makes termites a genuine risk for older timber homes. Here is what sellers need to understand about disclosure, treatment, documentation, and how to manage buyer confidence honestly.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Termites are a fact of life in Brisbane's inner east. The subtropical climate, the prevalence of older Queenslander and postwar timber-framed homes, and the general presence of moisture and organic matter in established suburbs all create conditions that termites exploit. This does not mean every home has a problem, but it does mean every seller in this market needs to understand where they stand, what they are obliged to disclose, and how to handle any history of termite activity before going to market.</p>

      <p>Buyers in Brisbane's inner east are not naive about termites. Most will commission a building and pest inspection as a matter of course, and their inspector will be specifically looking for evidence of activity, past damage, and the adequacy of any existing management system. A well-managed property with good documentation will not deter serious buyers. A property where termite history appears to have been hidden, or where obvious damage has been repainted over without treatment, will lose buyers quickly and legitimately.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Your disclosure obligations as a Queensland seller</h2>
      <p>In Queensland, sellers are required to disclose known latent defects in a property. A latent defect is something that would not be apparent to a buyer on a reasonable inspection. Known termite damage that has been concealed behind plaster or paint, or a known history of active termite activity, falls into this category. If you are aware of it and do not disclose it, you are exposed to claims of misrepresentation and potential liability for the buyer's remediation costs after settlement.</p>

      <p>The contract of sale in Queensland includes a body corporate disclosure (for strata properties) and a seller's disclosure statement, but the broader common law obligation to not actively mislead a buyer applies regardless of what specific boxes are ticked. If you know something, disclose it. The practical risk of concealment almost always outweighs any short-term benefit to the sale price.</p>

      <p>Disclosure does not prevent a sale. A property with a known and fully treated termite history, supported by documentation, sells. The buyer may negotiate, but they negotiate with full information and the transaction proceeds on an honest basis. Properties where termite history surfaces during the B&P inspection, with no prior disclosure and no treatment documentation, tend to lose buyers entirely or result in very aggressive price reductions at the worst possible moment in the negotiation.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The difference between a termite management system and a pest inspection</h2>
      <p>These two things are often confused, and the confusion matters when you are selling. A termite management system is an ongoing protective measure installed and maintained to prevent termite ingress. It might be a chemical barrier applied to the soil around the building's perimeter, a bait station network, or a combination of both. A current, maintained system means the property has active protection in place. It does not mean the property has never had termites, and it does not eliminate the need for an annual inspection.</p>

      <p>A building and pest inspection is a point-in-time assessment conducted by a licensed inspector, typically engaged by a buyer under a due diligence clause in the contract. The inspector looks for current and historical evidence of termite activity and damage across the entire building, assesses the condition and adequacy of any management system, and identifies conducive conditions such as timber-to-soil contact, moisture problems, or debris near the structure. They report their findings in writing. The report goes to the buyer and becomes part of their decision to proceed, renegotiate, or withdraw.</p>

      <p>As a seller, you can commission your own building and pest inspection before listing. This is worth doing in almost every circumstance. It gives you full visibility of what a buyer's inspector is likely to find, allows you to address any issues before they become contract renegotiation ammunition, and demonstrates to buyers that you are a transparent vendor. A pre-sale B&P is not a guarantee that the buyer's inspector will find nothing different, but it significantly reduces the likelihood of a late-stage surprise.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What to do if you find active termites or significant past damage</h2>
      <p>If you discover active termite activity or significant structural damage before listing, the sequence matters. Treat first. Engage a licensed pest controller to assess the extent of the infestation, apply the appropriate treatment (which may involve baiting, chemical application, or both), and obtain a written clearance report once treatment is complete. Do not list the property with an active infestation in place.</p>

      <p>If structural damage exists, have it properly assessed by a builder or structural engineer. Minor cosmetic damage to non-structural timber can often be repaired without significant cost. Structural damage requires remediation by a licensed builder with documentation. Buyers and their inspectors will be able to tell the difference between properly repaired timber and a repaint over damaged material. The former is acceptable and manageable. The latter will be flagged in the B&P report and will cause problems.</p>

      <p>Once treatment and remediation are complete, assemble your documentation: the treatment records, the pest controller's warranty, the clearance report, and any builder's invoices for remediation work. These documents are your evidence that the issue was identified, treated professionally, and resolved. Present them proactively to buyers at or before the due diligence period. This approach consistently produces better outcomes than waiting for the buyer to find something and then trying to explain it.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Documentation sellers should have ready</h2>
      <p>Whether or not you have a known termite history, having the following documentation ready before you list makes the due diligence process smoother and reduces the likelihood of late-stage renegotiation. Your licensed pest controller should be able to provide copies of anything they have issued.</p>

      <p>The most useful documents are: the most recent annual termite inspection report, any treatment records from the past five to ten years, the current warranty on the termite management system (if applicable), and any clearance reports issued after treatment. If the property has had termite damage repaired, the builder's invoice and a photo record of the work are also worth having.</p>

      <p>Annual termite inspections are a standard recommendation for all Brisbane homes, but particularly for older timber-framed properties. If your most recent inspection is more than 12 months old, commission a new one before listing. A current inspection report in the disclosure package signals to buyers that the property is well-maintained and that you are not trying to hide anything.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Properties most at risk in Brisbane's inner east</h2>
      <p>The homes that face the highest termite risk in suburbs like Morningside, Hawthorne, Bulimba, Camp Hill, Norman Park, and Carina are overwhelmingly pre-1980 timber-framed Queenslanders and postwar fibro or hardwood homes. These properties have large volumes of structural and decorative timber, are often elevated on stumps (which creates soil contact points), and have had decades of exposure. This does not mean they are in poor condition. Many are extremely well-maintained. But it does mean that termite management history is a relevant question for almost every one of them.</p>

      <p>Newer properties, or properties that have been comprehensively restumped and rewired with steel and concrete subfloor structures, face lower risk. But termites are resourceful and will exploit any available cellulose material, so no property is entirely without exposure. The difference is the baseline risk profile and the type of damage a termite incursion is likely to cause.</p>

      <p>If your property is a pre-1980 timber Queenslander and you do not have current termite inspection and management documentation, getting that in order before listing is one of the more straightforward pre-sale steps you can take. It costs relatively little, it protects you from late-stage surprises, and it signals to the market that the property has been properly looked after.</p>

      <div style="padding:1.5rem;background:rgba(245,208,122,0.06);border-left:3px solid #f5d07a;">
        <p style="font-size:0.88rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.8;"><strong style="color:#f5d07a;">Getting ready to sell?</strong> Daniel works across Brisbane's inner east and can give you honest advice on what pre-sale steps will make the most difference for your specific property. No obligation. <a href="/contact" style="color:#f5d07a;font-weight:600;">Get in touch.</a></p>
      </div>

    </div>
  </div>
</article>
